    "summary": "Tiglath-Pileser III (r. 745–727 BC) was the king who transformed the Neo-Assyrian state from a powerful but regionally focused kingdom into a true empire — through administrative, military, and political reforms that became the model for all subsequent ancient Near Eastern empires. He reorganized the army from a system dependent on seasonal levies to a professional standing force, reorganized the empire's provincial structure to replace autonomous vassal kings with directly controlled provinces governed by Assyrian officials, and systematized the mass deportation policy as a tool of demographic and political control.\n\nHis campaigns conquered the northern kingdom of Israel (see [[event:3082|Assyrian Conquest Israel]]), subjugated Urartu and much of Anatolia, extended control over Babylonia (where he ruled as king under the Babylonian name Pulu), and pushed to the borders of Egypt. The biblical accounts of his reign in 2 Kings portray him as the instrument of divine punishment on the unfaithful Israelites. Tiglath-Pileser's administrative innovations were adopted wholesale by his successors and later by the Achaemenid Persian Empire — the satrap system and royal road network echo his provincial reorganization. He is arguably the single most important architect of Assyrian imperial power.",
